&gt;     &gt; 
&gt;     &gt; --- Vladimir Bossicard &lt;vladimir@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;     &gt; &gt; &gt; The Junit.org site has an FAQ section
&gt;     &gt; &gt; &gt; (http://junit.sourceforge.net/doc/faq/faq.htm) with 
&gt;     &gt; the following
&gt;     &gt; &gt; &gt; question: How do I implement a test case for a thrown 
&gt;     &gt; exception?
&gt;     &gt; &gt; &gt; 
&gt;     &gt; &gt; &gt; The answer they give is not completely correct because it
&gt; does
&gt;     &gt; &gt; not
&gt;     &gt; &gt; &gt; account for the possiblility that another exception could
&gt; be
&gt;     &gt; &gt; thrown.
&gt;     &gt; &gt; 
&gt;     &gt; &gt; I think they assume that your method only throws one 
&gt;     &gt; exception.  If
&gt;     &gt; &gt; your method throws more exceptions, you can use:
&gt;     &gt; &gt; 
&gt;     &gt; &gt; // Test IllegalArgumentException is thrown when 
&gt;     &gt; partnerID is null.
&gt;     &gt; &gt; public void test_00_isPartnerAssigned() {
&gt;     &gt; &gt;    try {
&gt;     &gt; &gt;       boolean assignedStatus =
&gt;     &gt; &gt;         
&gt; instancePartnerHierarchyWorker.isPartnerAssigned(null);
&gt;     &gt; &gt;    } catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {
&gt;     &gt; &gt;       return;
&gt;     &gt; &gt;    } catch (Exception e) {
&gt;     &gt; &gt;       fail(&quot;IllegalArgumentException should have been
&gt; thrown.&quot;);
&gt;     &gt; &gt;    }
&gt;     &gt; &gt;    fail(&quot;IllegalArgumentException should have been
&gt; thrown.&quot;);
&gt;     &gt; &gt; }
&gt;     &gt; &gt; 
